      Under point #2, often "results stay only within their professional community" because the professional journals in which those results appear are run by private publishers who charge very hefty subscription fees, and for non-subscribers, impose prohibitively high reprint charges to view individual articles.<br/><br/>Agencies who fund research should make any necessary arrangements with researchers and publishers to ensure that any published results should also be made available to the public for no additional charge. After all, we already paid for it.

                  
    </td>
  </tr>


